  "articleSummary": "The article argues that many sites adopt hosted search services like Algolia prematurely, when a simpler, build-time solution like Pagefind suffices. Its core thesis is that if the search index can be rebuilt from the same static HTML users browse, Pagefind avoids the synchronization complexity and operational overhead of a second system. The tone is analytical and pragmatic, using the metaphor “infrastructure cosplay” to frame unnecessary complexity. The intended audience is developers and technical decision-makers building content sites (blogs, docs, marketing pages) who need a clear decision rule: start with Pagefind for static content, and only reach for Algolia when live writes, user-specific ranking, or business rules are required.",
